Modeling relationships

Challenges

  • Two core statistical challenges
    • Randomness - a challenge for inference
    • Endogeneity - a challenge for identification


  • Randomness: all statistical estimates are random
    • Sampling variation
    • Modeled variation


  • Endogeneity: changes in IV related to other factors affecting DV
  • Exogeneity: changes in IV unrelated to other factors affecting DV

Modeling relationships

Analytical approaches

  • Experiments
    • Lab, survey, field
    • Gold standard
    • Not always possible


  • Observational studies
    • Standard datasets


  • Natural experiments
    • Identify situation where values of IV are random, or at least exogenous
  • All strive for validity
    • Internal validity: inference (model) = unbiased
      • Endogeneity causes bias
    • External validity: inference applies generally
      • To unsampled data
      • To the world
      • a.k.a. generalizability

Ordinary least squares regression model

\[y_{i} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}x_{i} + \epsilon_{i}\]

\(x_{i} = \) the independent variable (IV)

\(y_{i} = \) the dependent variable (DV)

\(\beta_{0} = \) the intercept or the constant; indicates where the regression line crosses the y-axis; it is the expected value of y when x = 0

\(\beta_{1} = \) the slope; indicates how much change in y is expected if x increases by one unit; almost always more interesting than \(\beta_{0} \)

\(\epsilon_{i} = \) the error or the residual; portion of y not explained by x

OLS model: distribution of estimates

\(\widehat\beta_{1} = 2.29\) (from income/vote model)

  • \(\widehat\beta_{1} = random\)
    • \(\widehat{Y}_{i} \) is part of the equation for \(\widehat\beta_{1}\)
    • \(\widehat{Y}_{i} \) depends on \(\epsilon_{i} \), which is random


Randomness occurs in two ways: sampling & modeled variation

  • Sampling variation results from the randomness of the observations selected into the sample from the population

  • Modeled variation results from the inherent randomness in the data generated even when data is measured for an entire population

OLS model: distribution of estimates

A probability distribution is a graph or formula that gives the probability of each value of a random variable

The distribution of \(\widehat\beta_{1} \) will be normally distributed if either:

  • Sample size is large (Central Limit Theorem)

  • Errors \(\epsilon \) are normally distributed


  • CLT: the mean of a sufficient number of independent draws from any distribution will be normally distributed.

OLS model: bias in estimates

  • A biased coefficient estimate will systematically be higher or lower than the true value

  • An estimator is unbiased if the expected value equals the true value

  • Bias is almost always due to endogeneity

OLS model: precision of estimates

\[ Var(\widehat\beta_{1}) = \frac{\sigma^2}{N * var(X)} \]

\(\sigma^2 = variance~ of~ the~ regression\) (More in a bit)

OLS model: precision of estimates

As N increases, \(var(\widehat\beta_{1})\) decreases


OLS model: precision of estimates

Estimators are consistent if \(\widehat\beta_{1}\) converges to \(\beta_{1}\)


OLS model: precision of estimates

Probability limit (plim)

  • value to which an estimator converges as sample size gets very large

Consistency

  • estimators are consistent if the plim converges to the TRUE value
  • if the exogeneity requirement is met, estimators are consistent

OLS model: goodness of fit (GOF)

Remember that \(Var(\widehat\beta_{1}) = \frac{\sigma^2}{N * var(X)}\)

\(\sigma^2 = variance~ of~ the~ regression\) & measures how well the model explains the variation in Y

OLS model: goodness of fit (GOF)

\(R^2 = \) very popular measure of goodness of fit

  • the square of the correlation between the observed \(Y_{i}\) and predicted \(\widehat{Y_{i}}\) values

  • measures the linearity between \(X_{i}\) & \(Y_{i}\)

OLS diagnostics

Homoskedasticity: good

  • Errors (residuals) from regression observations all have constant variance
    • No discernible patterns when plotted against fitted values

Heteroskedasticity: bad

  • Errors (residuals) from regression observations DO NOT have constant variance
    • Discernible patterns when plotted against fitted values
    • Generally, errors are larger at one end of fitted values than the other


Another example: scale v. state fair weight guesser (p. 68 Bailey)

OLS diagnostics

Our model

OLS diagnostics

Impacts of heteroskedasticity

  • Does NOT BIAS estimates
  • However, the variance of estimates might be off (usually too low)

How to fix

  • Use a different formula for calculating variance of estimates
  • Heteroskedasticity-consistent errors (easy with software)

More formal tests for heteroskedasticity…stay tuned

OLS diagnostics

Errors uncorrelated with each other: No autocorrelation.

  • Normally applicable in two situations:
    • Data are clustered in some way
    • Data are time series

OLS diagnostics

Impacts of autocorrelation

  • Does NOT BIAS estimates
  • However, the variance of estimates might be off (usually too low)

How to fix

  • Use a different formula for calculating variance of estimates
  • Autocorrelation-consistent errors (easy with software)

More formal tests for autocorrelation…stay tuned

OLS diagnostics

Outliers & influential observations

  • Outlier: an observation that is very different from all the others
  • Influential observation: a single observation that has substantial impact on model estimates

OLS diagnostics

Outliers & influential observations

OLS diagnostics

Outliers & influential observations

OLS diagnostics

Outliers & influential observations:

  • Can be especially troublesome in smaller samples
  • Can exert undue influence over coefficient estimates

How to fix

  • Diagnose through plots & comparison
  • Inform readers of the issue
  • Follow-up: find out more about why the observation is unique
  • Report results with & without observation & compare
  • Justify including or excluding the observation

Slightly more formal tests for influence…stay tuned

Summary

  • Know your data (look at it)
  • Be aware of the potential for endogeneity & carefully construct models
  • Examine precision in estimates & overall model fit (GOF)
  • Perform regression diagnostics on all models
